<li id="cite_note-61"><b><a href="#cite_ref-61" title="">^</a></b> For example, the first line of the Bhagavad Gita is <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">dhṛtarāşţra uvāca</span>, which occurs immediately after the last line of the preceding chapter in the full Sanskrit text of the Mahabharata: | 6.23.1 <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">dhṛtarāşţra uvāca</span> | 6.23.1a <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">dharmakşetre kurukṣetre samavetā yuyutsavaḥ</span> || Source: Electronic text (C) Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Pune, India, 1999. Electronic edition downloaded from: <a href="http://bombay.indology.info/mahabharata/statement.html" class="external autonumber" title="http://bombay.indology.info/mahabharata/statement.html" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>.</li>
